Binary cross entropy (BCE) is a loss function commonly used in binary classification problems. It measures
 the difference between two probability distributions, typically the true labels and the predicted probabilities.

also called as the Log Loss

BCE = -(1/n)(sigma i=1 to n) (yi* loge(y^i) + (1-yi)* loge(1-y^i))

where yi is the true label (0 or 1) and y^i is the predicted probability of the positive class (between 0 and 1).\

yi = actual value while y^i is the predicted value by model

mostly for spam ham


eg-- 


Email                actual value         predicted value
A(spam)                 1                      0.9                  trick === if 1 then right half =0 as (1-yi) so only loge(0.9)
B(not spam)             0                     0.7           trick === if 0 then left half =0 as (yi) so only loge(1-0.7) = loge(0.3)
C(spam)                1                      0.4                  trick === if 1 then right half =0 as (1-yi) so only loge(0.4)


so final value = 
                        -(1/3)×(−2.22562)=0.74187



here the activation function used is sigmoid as we are dealing with binary 
classification and it converts the output of the model into a probability 
between 0 and 1. The sigmoid function takes a real-valued input and maps 
it to a value between 0 and 1, which can be interpreted as a probability 
for the positive class. This allows us to calculate the binary cross-entropy 
loss based on the predicted probabilities and the true labels.